<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="283" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1476,2043]" pageId="14" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1476,1502]" pageId="14" pageNumber="283">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name 
<taxonomicName authority="Madi-Ravazzi &amp; Segala &amp; Roman &amp; Alevi &amp; Prediger &amp; Yassin &amp; Hua-Van &amp; Miller, 2021" authorityName="Madi-Ravazzi &amp; Segala &amp; Roman &amp; Alevi &amp; Prediger &amp; Yassin &amp; Hua-Van &amp; Miller" authorityYear="2021" box="[458,612,1476,1502]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Drosophila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lehrmanae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[458,612,1476,1502]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="283">D. lehrmanae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[619,709,1476,1502]" pageId="14" pageNumber="283">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[619,709,1476,1502]" pageId="14" pageNumber="283" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
was chosen in honor of the Distinguished Professor Emerita Lee Ehrman, a student of Theodosius Dobzhansky and outstanding drosophilist at the State University of 
<collectingRegion box="[1294,1409,1512,1539]" country="United States of America" name="New York" pageId="14" pageNumber="283">New York</collectingRegion>
at Purchase, NY, 
<collectingCountry box="[323,382,1548,1574]" name="United States of America" pageId="14" pageNumber="283">USA</collectingCountry>
, who significantly contributed to our understanding of evolutionary and behavioral biology over the last 60 years of her academic career (
<bibRefCitation author="Kim, Y." box="[665,784,1584,1611]" pageId="14" pageNumber="283" pagination="229 - 230" refId="ref10606" refString="Kim, Y. (2005) Natural History of Lee Ehrman. Behavior Genetics, 35, 229 - 230. [2005] https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10519 - 005 - 3215 - 2" type="journal article" year="2005">Kim 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="283" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1476,2043]" pageId="14" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1620,1646]" pageId="14" pageNumber="283">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
On closer examination, 
<taxonomicName authority="Madi-Ravazzi &amp; Segala &amp; Roman &amp; Alevi &amp; Prediger &amp; Yassin &amp; Hua-Van &amp; Miller, 2021" authorityName="Madi-Ravazzi &amp; Segala &amp; Roman &amp; Alevi &amp; Prediger &amp; Yassin &amp; Hua-Van &amp; Miller" authorityYear="2021" box="[595,750,1620,1646]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Drosophila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lehrmanae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[595,750,1620,1646]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="283">D. lehrmanae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[756,846,1620,1646]" pageId="14" pageNumber="283">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[756,846,1620,1646]" pageId="14" pageNumber="283" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dobzhansky &amp; Pavan" authorityYear="1943" box="[993,1148,1621,1646]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Drosophila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sturtevanti">
<emphasis box="[993,1148,1621,1646]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="283">D. sturtevanti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the following diagnostic characters: The body coloration (mesonotum, pleura, scutellum and abdomen) is lighter; the antennae are dark brown; females: the spot on the sixth tergite is smaller and its format is more like a circle than a half-moon; the spermatheca presents two collars instead of one; males: the aedeagus presents a relatively shorter apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="284" pageId="14" pageNumber="283" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1476,2043]" pageId="14" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,421,1764,1790]" pageId="14" pageNumber="283">Description. Male.</emphasis>
Head: Arista with 4-5 dorsal and 2 ventral branches, with bifurcated termination. Antennae dark brown, the proximal segment (pedicel) presents the light brown margins. Front velvety brown with area around ocellar triangle and around the orbital bristles light brown. Ocellar triangle and region of orbital setae darker. Anterior orbital about 1/3 posterior and middle orbital setae. Carina light brown, not sulcate, slightly prominent, and with small bristles below. Palpi light brown, pollinose, with bristles on the ventral surface and one very prominent on the end. Two prominent oral bristles. Greatest width of the cheeks about 1/6 to 1/8 greatest diameter of eye. Eyes dark red with a short dark pile.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1476,2043]" lastBlockId="15.[151,1437,151,933]" lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="284" pageId="14" pageNumber="283">Thorax: mesonotum light brown, it presents two darker uninterrupted longitudinal stripes in the central region, which extends from the anterior portion of the mesonotum and continues until the end of scutellum. It also presents a darker longitudinal stripe on each side, interrupted approximately in the first anterior quartile of the mesonotum and it does not continue until the scutellum. Acrostichal hairs in 6 rows. No prescutellars. Anterior scutellars parallel. Halteres light color. Scutellum light brown with indistinct continuations of the darker stripes of the mesonotum. Pleurae brown. Anterior sternopleural 1/3 posterior and much thinner. Coxae, femora, tibiae and tarsos yellowish brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,933]" box="[199,1237,367,393]" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">Abdomen: light brown with a longitudinal dark stripe on the inferior margins of each tergite.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">Male terminalia: The dorso-ventral region of the epandrium is angular. The cercus is U-shaped, covered with cercal bristles. The surstyli are large and concave and they are connected by a small subepandrial sclerite (decasternum).</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,933]" box="[199,725,511,537]" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">Wings: Wings hyalines. Costal index 1.8—2.0.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,933]" box="[199,445,547,573]" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">
Body length: 
<quantity box="[352,441,547,573]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="15" pageNumber="284" unit="mm" value="2.4">2.4 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,296,583,609]" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">Female:</emphasis>
The body features are the same as in males, but the sixth tergite is lighter and it presents a small opaque circular spot on each side. Approximately eight days after the puparia hatch, the adult female shows a clear contour in the opaque circular area of the sixth tergite.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,933]" box="[199,453,691,717]" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">Costal index 2.0—2.2.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,933]" box="[199,445,727,753]" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">
Body length: 
<quantity box="[352,441,727,753]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" pageId="15" pageNumber="284" unit="mm" value="3.1">3.1 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="284" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">
The main morphological characteristics of the species included in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dobzhansky &amp; Pavan" authorityYear="1943" box="[986,1106,763,788]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Drosophila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="284" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sturtevanti">
<emphasis box="[986,1106,763,788]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">sturtevanti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup described in works in the literature were compared with those of new species 
<taxonomicName authority="Madi-Ravazzi &amp; Segala &amp; Roman &amp; Alevi &amp; Prediger &amp; Yassin &amp; Hua-Van &amp; Miller, 2021" authorityName="Madi-Ravazzi &amp; Segala &amp; Roman &amp; Alevi &amp; Prediger &amp; Yassin &amp; Hua-Van &amp; Miller" authorityYear="2021" box="[803,1056,799,825]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Drosophila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="284" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lehrmanae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[803,1056,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">Drosophila lehrmanae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1063,1153,799,825]" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1063,1153,799,825]" pageId="15" pageNumber="284" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<tableCitation box="[1169,1256,798,825]" captionStart="TABLE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,231,606,629]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="TABLE 9. The main morphological characteristics of the species included in the sturtevanti subgroup described in works in the literature were compared with those of new species Drosophila lehrmanae sp. nov." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/49AD6679FF81AA4DF19DD43FFED36484" pageId="15" pageNumber="284" tableUuid="49AD6679FF81AA4DF19DD43FFED36484">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1169,1256,798,825]" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">Table 9</emphasis>
</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">
The genetic markers also were also able to distinguish the species, for COI5’ there were 23, 26 and 23 mutation, for COI3’there were 28, 26 and 25, COII 20, 19 and 18 and for ND4 15, 13 and 9 comparing with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mourao &amp; Bicudo" authorityYear="1967" box="[1256,1395,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Drosophila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="284" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dacunhai">
<emphasis box="[1256,1395,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">D. dacunhai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Magalhaes" authorityYear="1962" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Drosophila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="284" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="milleri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">D. milleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dobzhansky &amp; Pavan" authorityYear="1943" box="[280,434,907,932]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Drosophila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="284" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sturtevanti">
<emphasis box="[280,434,907,932]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">D. sturtevanti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, respectively. The mutation and its sites are seen in 
<tableCitation box="[1017,1118,906,933]" captionStart="TABLE 10" captionStartId="15.[151,239,980,1004]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="TABLE 10. Mutation site of D. lerhmanae sp. nov and other species of the sturtevanti subgroup for 4 mitochondrial" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/49AD6679FF83AA4FF19DD5B5FF766207" pageId="15" pageNumber="284" tableUuid="49AD6679FF83AA4FF19DD5B5FF766207">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1017,1118,906,933]" pageId="15" pageNumber="284">Table 10</emphasis>
</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
